        <p class="project-title">Minesweeper!</p>
        <p>
          I started by coding my first ever project to be a full-featured clone of classic windows minesweeper using <strong>JavaScript, HTML, and CSS</strong>. 
          I learned about border images, sprites, concurrent mouse events, and got in some great CSS experience while reskinnning the whole thing.
          Much regrettable code and my first brush with recursion ensued. When I finished a couple of days early, I built another theme for it. Psychedelic! 
          <a href="https://forrest216.github.io/minesweeper/" target="_blank"><button>Check it out!</button></a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <img class="projects-image" src="images/minesweeper.gif" alt="Kaboom!">
    </div>
    <div class="projects-content">
      <img class="projects-image" src="images/teambridge.jpg" alt="Bronze me!">
      <div class="project-text-container">
        <p class="project-title">LinkedIn Hackathon Project</p>
        <p>
          Built in a weekend for LinkedIn's first hackathon using <strong>React, Express, Node.js, MongoDB, and Python</strong> in collaboration with a design team.
          I learned about the design/dev workflow, pair programming, and got some more experience coding under tight time constraints.
          We impressed the judges by independently conceiving of and building a now-deprecated LinkedIn feature, propelling us to 3rd place! 
          <a href="https://github.com/forrest216/linkedin-hackathon" target="_blank"><button>Check it out!</button></a>       
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="projects-content">
      <div class="project-text-container">
        <p class="project-title">Pi-Hole with AMOLED display</p>
        <p>
          Using <strong>Python, Bash, and SSH</strong>, I installed <a href="https://pi-hole.net/" target="_blank">Pi-Hole software</a> on a Raspberry Pi Zero W. 
          I then soldered headers onto the Zero, loaded code via SSH, attached the display, and customized the output. 
          After directing my router to handle DNS through the Raspberry Pi's IP address, every device on my home network now has DNS ad-blocking!
          I got to practice soldering(I need a better iron, but I freakin nailed it!) and worked some Bash/Nano magic.
          <a href="https://github.com/forrest216/pi-hole" target="_blank"><button>Check it out!</button></a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <img class="projects-image" src="images/pi-hole.jpg" alt="ZAP!">
    </div>
    <div class="projects-content">
      <img class="projects-image" src="images/deepwoods.png" alt="DeepWoods">
      <div class="project-text-container">
        <p class="project-title">DeepWoods</p>
        <p>
          For my first <strong>MongoDB/Express/Node.JS</strong> app, I built a secret stash and trade app for foragers.
          Utilising the Google Maps API and OAuth, users store their secret mushroom spots for later reference. 
          Your secrets can then be traded to other users for theirs on the exchange. I spent a lot of extra time on CSS and making DeepWoods responsive.
          I learned a ton about the Maps API and RESTful routing. What a week!
          <a href="http://deepwoods.herokuapp.com/" target="_blank"><button>Check it out!</button></a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="projects-content">
